The raw unadjusted WAR rankings suggest that it would be very unlikely for Trout to end his career with more WAR than old time great players like Babe Ruth and Ty Cobb. However, our era-adjustment method tells a slightly different story if Trout can stay healthy. Through the 2021 season Mike Trout is ranked 54th in career ebWAR and 41st in career efWAR. We can see that Stargell was one of the most prolific power hitters of all-time when one takes into account the following facts: the extended pitching dominance in the 60s, the post-integration surge of players into the 1970s, and his long time home park Forbes Field was notoriously hard on left-handed batters. It is interesting to see what speculation was written about Stargell in the second to last paragraph of his SABR bio:

âAt the time of his retirement, Stargellâs 475 home runs tied him with Stan Musial for 15th on the all-time list. As legendary a power hitter as he was, one is still tempted to ask, âWhat if?â What if he hadnât played eight-and-a-half years in the home run graveyard of Forbes Field? What if his knees had held up? What if he had been more serious about staying in shape early in his career? Four-hundred-seventy-five home runs, of course, is an extraordinary achievement. But one could imagine how a consistently healthy, consistently fit Stargell shooting at a more inviting right field porch could have boosted that total to well over 500; maybe even, as he suggested himself, close to 600."

Our method has Stargell at 526 era-adjusted home runs when we project his career in to the context beginning in 1977, which, although 526 is still far from 600, it is easy to imagine that a healthy Stargell would be close to 600. If one were to project his stats into the launch angle and exit velolicity context of the current era (current at the time that this was written) then Stargellâs totals should be right around 600. So Willie Stargell got it right. He would hit close to 600 home runs, if he were consistently fit and moved to a more forgiving ball park. Willie Stargell is a casuality of the WAR movement and era-adjusted WAR does not revitalize his image. But we should think of Stargell as one of the most efficient and prolific home run hitters of all time. This is the mental image we should have in mind when we think of Willie Stargell.

Max Scherzer

Max Scherzer is one of this eraâs greatest pitchers. He is one of a handfull of pitchers to win 3 Cy Young awards. Other players with 3 Cy Young awards include Roger Clemens, Randy Johnson, Greg Maddux, Steve Carlton, Tom Seaver, Pedro Martinez, Clayton Kershaw, Sandy Koufax, and Jim Palmer. Scherzerâs run from 2013-2019 is especially dominant. Over that stretch he collected his Cy Young awards and never fell below fifth in the voting. That being said, his numbers over that strecth do not leap off of the page. Sure, his strikeout rates and strike outs per walk ratios are all-time elite, but ERA and most counting totals do not reflect the Cy Young voting when viewed from the lens of baseball history. Take Tom Seaver as an example. From 1969 to 1975 Terrific Tom boasted similar dominance and also collected 3 Cy Young awards. In 1971 Seaver had a 1.76 ERA over 286.1 innings. Surely his run leaps off the page.

Max Scherzerâs dominance is punished by his era, a time period with a large MLB eligible talent pool, lower innings totals, and a balance of hitting and pitching that was tilted in the favor of pitching which, in this case, led to a crowded field of low ERA totals. Our per season era-adjusted statistics paint a more favorable comparison of Scherzerâs dominant 7-year run to that of Seaverâs:

The Babe Ruth anomaly

Babe Ruth revolutionized baseball by prioritizing home run hitting as the MLB livened the baseball. As stated here, the single season home run record before Babe Ruth was 27 by Ned Williamson in 1884. Babe Ruth broke this record in 1919 when he hit 29 home runs. He subsequently destroyed his own record in the following 1920 season when he hit 54 home runs. The runner up in 1920 finished the season with only 15 home runs. This level of dominance has never been seen before and has never been seen since, and it poses a problem for era-adjustment techniques.

Babe Ruthâs dominance is in part due to his talent, but is also in part to him exercising a superior batting strategy that had not existed before. Therefore, Ruthâs âvs his peersâ stats are slightly distorted, and his era-adjusted stats will also be distorted as a result. Ruthâs era-adjusted stats reflect the combination of his talent and his competitive advantage. This competitive advantage does not exist in other contexts. Our method will therefore overestimate Ruthâs era-adjusted home run hitting and his era-adjusted WAR since our method does not yet disentangle talent and competitive circumstance. The problem of the Babe Ruth anomaly confounds all era-adjustment techniques. We imagine that Ruthâs era-adjusted OBP is also overestimated by our method. The Babe Ruth anomaly challenges all other era-adjustment techniques, and is especially challenging for anyone making interpretations based solely on raw or league adjusted â+â stats.

The Tony Gwynn anomaly

Tony Gwynn has the highest era-adjusted batting average by a mile (See part I). He was a truly amazing hitter who stood very far from his peers. However, like Babe Ruth, a portion of his dominance is due to circumstance. Gywnn was one of the early pioneers of using film to study his strengths and weaknesses as well as the strengths and weaknesses of the pitchers that he faced. Nowadays film study is a basic training method available to everyone in the MLB, and it is unusual and worth mentioning when great players do not use it. Therefore, like Ruth, Gwynnâs batting average stats are slightly distorted, and his era-adjusted stats will also be distorted as a result. Like Ruth, Gwynnâs era-adjusted stats reflect the combination of his talent and his competitive advantage. Our method will therefore overestimate Gwynnâs era-adjusted batting average and his era-adjusted WAR as a result.

WAR and itâs usage in HOF discussions

One of the goals of WAR is to provide a framework for people like us to compare players across eras. The following passage is taken directly from the What is WAR? page on FanGraphs:

âThe goal of WAR is to provide a holistic metric of player value that allows for comparisons across team, league, year, and era and a framework for player evaluation.â

The work in this article moves WAR closer to its goal of providing fair comparisons of players who have played in vastly different eras. This matters when we evaluate a playerâs career in historical context. The HOF players of the old past are beneficiaries of biased performance metrics. Comparisons based upon âvs your peersâ statistics are therefore slanted in favor of old time playersâspecifically those who performed in the segregated NL/AL. With out method, this is no more. Todd Helton

Letâs focus now on the HOF candidacy for a player on this list, say Todd Helton. Jay Jaffe wrote an article on Heltonâs candidacy. In it, he said

âWith all facets of his game taken together, Heltonâs 61.8 career WAR (bWAR) is 17th among first basemen, 5.1 WAR below the standard, and below 11 of the 21 enshrined including Bagwell, Thome, and Thomas, whose careers overlapped with his.â

Comparing a Player Outside His Era: Bill James and Tom Tango

Bill James published a fascinating conversation between Tom Tango and himself on the subject of cross-era comparisons. There are many nuggets from this conversation which deserve attention, but in the interest of brevity, we will only focus on a few segments.

Simplifying a little, Tom Tangoâs initial position is that we should only compare players to their contemporaries in the strictest of senses. He says:

âYou have about 12-15 nonpitcher in the HOF for any 10-11 year time period. If Andruw Jones [a player whose HOF candidcay that Bill and Tom are discussing] is one of the top 12 nonpitcher among his peers, great. If heâs one of the 40 nonpitchers born 1962-1992, great. (Though these numbers can be argued based on expansion.)â¦ This way, we donât have to makeâtimeline" adjustments. Thatâs me though."

Billâs response is very lengthy (although not as lengthy as what you have read here). One of his main points of response is:

"Yes, of course it is difficult to make cross-generational comparisons in baseball, but you ignore the fact that we have a constant frame of reference which applies across time and which stabilizes the data across time: Wins. IF you can state a playerâs contribution to his team in terms of wins and losses, then you have a valid basis for comparing a player from 1968 to a player in 2008âleaving only the large problem of the relative quality of play over time, and the relatively small issues of the length of the schedule and what to do with post-season play.

And, in fact, we HAVE 85% solved the problem(s) of stating a playerâs contribution to his team in terms of wins and losses. Yes, we still have the WAR/Wins and Losses Issue and the many problems inherent in WAR, but what we DO know about this issue now is much larger than what we do not knowâunlike 1975, when we had not even reached the understanding that we needed to state these contributions in constant terms, and that wins was the constant unit which guides the debate.

Tom responds with:

"Inherent in the wins-as-the-great-equalizer debate is that it treats winning percentage of .500 as a constant. This forces a specific mindset: (a) do you adjust this across time, so that a .500 win% in 1917 is not the same as in 2017? (b) do you accept it is the same, solely for the purposes of peer-comparisons?

If you accept (b), weâre holding the players accountable to their era only. And so any comparison of Ty Cobb to Rickey Henderson is limited to their comparisons to their direct peers, and then players of the early 1900s, as a group, are being treated as equals to the players of the 1980s and of today (.500 = .500). So, weâre actually comparing Cobb and Rickey through this âcommon baselineâ.

If you accept (a), you need to accept that players have gotten better across time, just like in every other sport, and so, the average player in Cobbâs time would likely be a bench player today, at best. I say this not only because players must have gotten physically stronger and faster, but also because 3/8ths of the best players today would have been precluded from playing during the segregation era. If we use players of the 1900s as any kind of benchmark, by this assumption, weâd be voting in ten players every year.

In my view, before we jump through the hoops that a careful timeline comparison would require, (including establishing which of the two assumptions to follow, of which no one will agree with anyway) letâs at least do the easy part and compare players to their direct peers."

In our view, the Full House Model IS the careful timeline comparison sought by Tom Tango, and it renders his mindset distinctions between (a) and (b) moot. The Full House Model takes statistics like WAR and corrects for its existing era-biases through a balancing of how one performs âvs their peersâ and how many people are eligible to play in the MLB.

Tom is right when he suggests that we would be voting in more players every year if we actually approach HOF candidates by their era-adjusted talent. It seems that he is stating this as a drawback which, if true, would be very disappointing considering that older playersâ statistics are inflated as a result of racial segregation.

ESPNâs Top 100 MLB players of all time, Buster Olney and Christina Kahrl

In February 2022, ESPN published a new top 100 ranking list, you can see it here. Their list was compiled in essentially two steps. As quoted from the linked article:

First, they selected a pool of 200 candidate players using career WAR, Hall of Fame status, peak performance and overall contributions to the game as initial screening criteria. They then asked dozens of ESPN editors and writers to contribute to a balloting system that pits players from the list against each other in head-to-head voting. The question they posed: âBased on a combination of career value and peak performance, which player would you rank higher?â ESPNâs participants voted more than 20,000 times. Based on those votes, the players were ranked by the percentage of the time they were chosen over any competing player.

The ESPN top 100 list included 6 players who began their career before baseball was integrated in their top 10, and 11 such players in their top 25. By our calculations, the chance of observing 11 or more pre-integration players in a top 25 list is around 1 in 250, and the chance of observing 6 or more pre-integration players in a top 10 list is around 1 in 200. Thus, ESPN has yet again included too many old time players in their rankings of the greatest all-time players.

One redeeming aspect about ESPNâs list is the discussion between Olney, Doolittle, Keown, Passan, Schoenfield, and Gonzalez that was published shortly after their list was released. Buster Olney started every round with all-around great takes regarding NL/AL players, and many others provided several additional great takes concerning such players while Passan was clearly drunk on nostalgia: âbUT RuTh Is A gUy WhO hIt MoRe HoMeRuNs ThAn EnTiRe TeAmS,â yawn. We especially appreciated how Olney started the show with his answer to the question: âWhat is the No.Â 1 thing that stands out to you when looking at our top 100?â

Thatâs funâ¦ but there are too many George Mikans mixed in with the LeBrons, so to speak, in a sport that has evolved just as much as the NBA or the NFL.â

In a previous article Eck stated: âSuperior statistical accomplishments achieved by players who started their careers way back in the day are a reflection of the inability to properly compare talent across eras.â Thank you Buster Olney!

Olney and othersâ reminds us of Christina Kahrlâs excellent 2016 article on problems with using poorly calibrated âvs your peersâ statistics to compare players across eras. Specifically, she said:

âThe Gehrig and Wagner arguments boil down to this: Via WAR or OPS+ or your own understanding of all of the numbers we have, you have faith in our measuring their relative extraordinary superiority over their peers in smaller leagues with deliberate personnel limitations and an uneven distribution of talent. You can have that faith, and it relies on a lot of data for support â at the same time that you turn a blind eye to whatâs going on in the game that creates that data.â

This is a point that is routinely missed among baseball fans and analysts alike, in part because they have been duped by websites claiming that the metrics they use are era-adjusted. Perhaps these people prefer a simple black and white world where, for example, 80+ WAR means youâre a Hall of Famer. Or perhaps, they are simply not willing to grapple with what the difficulties of what âera-adjustedâ ought to mean. In short, for a metric to be era-adjusted it needs to account for the changing distributions of league statistics and the changing composition of MLB players. The plot below depicts the WAR of a 2021 hypothetical replacement level batter (0 WAR) projected into every past season, the major shifts correspond to the integration of baseball and WWII, and the influx of Asian players in the mid-1990s. It is of interest to note that a replacement level player in 2021 is projected to produce about 3 WAR before 1950 (the really old seasons have fewer games). Thus the baseline quantity for which players are judged, the replacemant player is a moving target that is getting better over time. It is interesting to note that the plot below aesthetically resembles a zoomed-out version of Stephen Jay Gouldâs punctuated equilibrium applied to changes in the fossil record.

Szymborski refers to Soto as breaking ZiPS. In other words, the projection system is unreliable for Soto. We do not think that players break projection systems.
